[Martyn Edelsten <Martyn.Edelsten@ED.AC.UK> reminded me that this is
presumably malignant catarrhal fever. It is an inapparent infection of
black (and blue?) wildebeest. MCF is caused by Alcelaphine herpes virus
group I, and the virus is excreted at parturition. Cattle infected by
contact with wildebeest or infected placentae. Indigenous and exotic cattle
susceptible. Normally sporadic cases in cattle. Case mortality approaches
100%. Vertical and horizontal transmission occurs in wildebeest herds with
all calves infected within first few months of life. There is no vaccine.
Nothing to do except keep cattle away from wildebeest or vice versa!

For the real expert contact Hugh Reid at the Moredun Res Inst.
HReid@ed.mri.ac.uk (it might be h.reid) - Mod. MHJ]
